d) Verifier: Retourne les infos du terrain en JSON si traité, sinon un message.
public function verifier($iddossier) {
    $dossier = Dossier_Terrain::with('terrain')->find($iddossier);
    if ($dossier && $dossier->etat == 'traité') {
        return response()->json($dossier->terrain);
    }
    return response()->json(['message' => 'dossier encours de traitement']);
}



/////
What is the goal of this function?

👉 It checks a dossier and:

If it is treated (traité) → return terrain data
If not → return a message
find($iddossier)
searches dossier by ID (primary key)
with('terrain')
loads related table Terrain
avoids extra SQL queries (eager loading)

👉 So Laravel fetches:

dossier
AND its terrain in one go


find() → get one record
with() → load relation
if ($dossier->etat) → check condition
response()->json() → return API data


  When do we use this verifier() function?
We use this kind of function when we want to:

🔥 CHECK something + RETURN RESULT
Typical cases:
check status (traité / nontraité)
verify user or record
validate condition before showing data
return JSON (API / AJAX)


Do we use these methods for API / JSON?

👉 YES — but NOT “one special method only”
👉 You can use any Laravel query method, as long as you return JSON.

SON/API only means:

“We return data in JSON format”

The methods you use are still normal Laravel methods:

find()
where()
with()
first()
exists()


  f NO API and NO JSON, what changes?

👉 Only ONE thing changes:

❌ You don’t return JSON
✔ You return a VIEW
nstead of:

return response()->json(...)

You use:

return view(...)
Example (same logic, NO API)
public function verifier($iddossier) {
    $dossier = Dossier_Terrain::with('terrain')->find($iddossier);

    if ($dossier && $dossier->etat == 'traité') {
        return view('dossier.ok', compact('dossier'));
    }

    return view('dossier.not_ok', ['message' => 'dossier encours de traitement']);
}
